ul
liWe added navigation buttons to activity stream items/li
liWe changed the default member avatar/li
liWe loaded common site-specific CSS styles into TinyMCE drop-down menus/li
liWe adaptednbsp;a href=http://helen.wordpress.com/2012/01/08/using-chosen-for-a-replacement-taxonomy-metabox/Helen Hou’s implementation/anbsp;of the Chosen multi-select list styling to simplify back-end metaboxes for multiple taxonomies/li
/ul
h3A note on custom contentnbsp;types, fields, and taxonomies/h3
pFor the Learning Resources Directory, I needed to create and maintainnbsp;custom post types, field groups, and taxonomies to support a rather complex data structure for metadata for our learning standards: thenbsp;a href=http://www.maine.gov/education/lres/pei/index.htmlMaine Learning Results/anbsp;andnbsp;a href=http://www.corestandards.org/the-standardsCommon Core State Standards/a./p
pAfter having tried nearly every plugin option (and combination), I settled onnbsp;a href=http://wp-types.com/WP Types amp; Views/anbsp;(now called WP-Toolset), which allowed me to rapidly prototype and improve data structures. Then, I usednbsp;a href=http://www.gravityforms.com/Gravity Forms/anbsp;to createnbsp;a href=http://mainelearning.net/resources/recommend/front-end forms/anbsp;to prompt educators to organize and classify their recommended resources./p
pThis work has only just begun, but WP-Toolset has provided all the features we’ve needed; indeed it can be compared favorably with the Blocks, Views, Panes, and Panels modules and functions for Drupal. Indeed, I’ll be experimenting with WP-Toolset’snbsp;a href=http://wp-types.com/home/cred/CRED feature/a to more easily integration between front-end forms and structured data./p
h2Today/h2
pThenbsp;a href=http://mainelearning.net/online community of practice/anbsp;has now been fully-functional since March, 2012. Since then,nbsp;the Department has approved 21 practice groupsnbsp;with 250 members; the more active groups have included: thenbsp;a href=http://mainelearning.net/groups/dlag/Digital Learning Advisory Group/a, thenbsp;a href=http://mainelearning.net/groups/cdln/Cross Discipline Literacy Network/anbsp;(and its 10 subgroups), thenbsp;a href=http://mainelearning.net/groups/arts-leaders/Maine Arts Education Leaders/anbsp;cohort, and thenbsp;a href=http://mainelearning.net/groups/dcs/Digital Citizenship in Schools/anbsp;discussion group. We recently added a space for service-learning coordinators and practitioners, and maintain a list of group and membership requests./p
pThenbsp;a href=http://mainelearning.net/resourceslearning resources directory/anbsp;has been tested by a variety of educators, with continuous improvements based on user feedback. The Arts Education cohort is developing a peer review process for those who ask for review of their submissions. Wikipedia-style ratings will be implemented next./p
pCurrently, program direction, platform administration, and community stewardship functions are being performed by myself (Jay Collier) and our back-end developer, Boone Gorges (core software developer for the collaboration software)./p
h2Next phase/h2
pWe’ve now been live for almost one year. As we approach the end of our current funding and contract cycles, the state of Maine has been working to sustain MaineLearning.net./p
ul
liThe Department of Education has been planning to initiate a public communications campaign and is seeking funding to fund program leadership and community stewardship through the next level of service, including those potential enhancements listed below./li
liThe state’s Office of Information Technology has been developing an RFP that will seek external vendors to providenbsp;Internet hosting, software management, and back-end development to support the continuous improvement of the platform when the current funding and contracts end this spring./li
/ul
pWith sufficient resources, we are considering many potential enhancements, including the following, all of which are possible within the current framework, given additional staffing:/p
h4Potential collaboration enhancements/h4
ul
liAllowing open group applications and selecting new groups based upon capacity/li
liProfessional development support, including organic groups for sustained collaboration between webinars, seminars, and workshops/li
liActive management of resource vetting teams, including rubric development, and credential design (badges)/li
liAvailability of sub-sites (blogs) for every group, upon request/li
/ul
h4Potential resource directory enhancements/h4
ul
liStatewide promotion for crowdsourced resource sharing/li
liSimplified resource submission interfaces and predefined search results/li
liMultiple levels of evaluation options, from thumbs up/down, to multi-question reviews, to peer review workflows/li
liExchange of vetting data (paradata) via US DOE Learning Registry and other repositories/li
liIngest of pre-existing learning resources, from vetted OERs to professional development objects, to community learning opportunities/li
/ul
h4Potential administrative initiatives/h4
ul
liGrant applications for funding from regional and national foundations/li
liConsulting with other jurisdictions that wish to replicate the model/li
liContributing lessons learned and custom add-ons back to the open-source community/li
liInvestigating viability of integrating ePortfolio and learning management (ScholarPress) features into the platform/li
/ul
h2Toward the future of learning/h2
pIn a href=http://www.maine.gov/doe/plan/index.htmlemEducation Evolving/em /a(a href=http://www.maine.gov/doe/plan/strategic_plan_web_final.pdfPDF/a) — Maine’s 2012 strategic plan for learning in Maine — Commissioner Bowen worked with educators around the state to define the challenges and opportunities of 21st-century education./p
blockquotepTo build on the great work being done in Maine’s schools today, and to move from a century-old model of schooling to a more effective, learner-centered approach in the process, will require a steady focus on a handful of core priorities organized around meeting the individual learning needs of all students …/p
pSuch a move won’t take place through the imposition of heavy-handed mandates or one-size-fits-all approaches from Augusta, but by building on the innovative work being done in schools across Maine already and by employing strategies to increase collaboration and sharing of best practices…./p
pAs Harvard’s Tony Wagner argues in his book emThe Global Achievement Gap/em, teaching has been and continues to be a largely solitary practice providing few opportunities for collaboration and sharing of best practices…/p
pWith the advent of nbsp;the Internet, the sharing of new ideas and new approaches to teaching can be far more readily facilitated. Instructional materials, research on best practices, and even videos of effective instructional methods can be shared instantly across the state and around the world./p
/blockquote
pCollaborative, learner-centered education is at the heart of Maine’s strategy for transforming learning communities for this new era and a href=http://MaineLearning.netMaineLearning.net/anbsp;supports that strategy./p
pemWatch an introduction to Innovations in Maine Learning, including the MaineLearning.net online community of practice and learning resources directory: a href=http://www.slideshare.net/collier/innovations-in-maine-educationhttp://www.slideshare.net/collier/innovations-in-maine-education/a/em/p
/p
pemThis case study was supported by the a href=http://maine.gov/doe/Maine Department of Education/a. An earlier version was partially funded by the British Columbia a href=http://www.bcerac.ca/Educational Resources Acquisition Consortium/a./em/p
